
[1]entice

   ENTI'CE, v.t. [L. titio, a firebrand.]

   1. To incite or instigate, by exciting hope or desire; usually in a bad
   sense; as, to entice one to evil. Hence, to seduce; to lead astray; to
   induce to sin, by promises or persuasions.

   My son, if sinners entice thee, consent thou not. Prov.1.

   2. To tempt; to incite; to urge or lead astray.

   Every man is tempted, when he is drawn away by his own lust, and
   enticed. James 1.

   3. To incite; to allure; in a good sense.
